01:18:40,274 --> 01:18:49,397
And at the time it was supported by this council and recommended that the mayor put a budget line item, which there is currently no budget line item to repave

844
01:18:49,853 --> 01:18:52,514
roads in our streets and our community.

845
01:18:53,435 --> 01:19:05,099
And I was hoping that I requested a million dollars and I was hoping that at least the mayor in good faith would recognize the need in this community and would put something towards a line item.

846
01:19:05,540 --> 01:19:13,383
But needless to say, Mr. President, that never amounted in the budget and never came to fruition.

847
01:19:14,503 --> 01:19:18,445
And it is one of the major concerns I have as a member of the council.

848
01:19:19,250 --> 01:19:20,792
um, the condition of our roads.

849
01:19:21,412 --> 01:19:33,982
So, uh, that is one issue, Mr. President, that I'm hoping, uh, that the mayor will, uh, uh, hear this loud and clear that, um, you know, when you have 950,000 or 980,000, the city puts forward.

850
01:19:38,382 --> 01:19:49,967
and then gets 100% of that back, so we get reimbursed 100%, then we have the $980,000 back, we should be reinvesting that $980,000 into roads.

851
01:19:51,667 --> 01:19:52,808
To me, that's a no-brainer.

852
01:19:53,088 --> 01:19:55,409
That should be a reinvestment right back into our roads.

853
01:19:55,809 --> 01:19:58,850
Instead, we're not using it for that purpose, Mr. President.

854
01:19:59,550 --> 01:20:06,673
And I would hope the mayor hears this loud and clear based on the information that I brought forward

855
01:20:07,322 --> 01:20:14,886
And the fact that our current way of doing business in the community is we're always going to be chasing our tail.

856
01:20:15,226 --> 01:20:16,907
We're never going to get ahead on our streets.

857
01:20:17,287 --> 01:20:20,388
We're always, every year, going to be facing, you know what?

858
01:20:20,408 --> 01:20:21,469
Look at all these potholes.

859
01:20:21,809 --> 01:20:22,529
Look at the curbs.

860
01:20:22,569 --> 01:20:23,930
They don't match the street.

861
01:20:23,970 --> 01:20:25,971
The curbs are the same level as the street.

862
01:20:26,233 --> 01:20:27,934
Look at the manhole covers, they're sinking.

863
01:20:28,214 --> 01:20:30,815
Look at the catch basins, they're all sinking in the community.

864
01:20:31,616 --> 01:20:37,859
This money, Mr. President, can be used, chapter 90 money, can be used for, according to our city engineer.

865
01:20:37,919 --> 01:20:42,722
In the back, can we cut the talking down to someone who's speaking?

866
01:20:43,942 --> 01:20:44,803
I apologize, Councilman.

867
01:20:44,823 --> 01:20:45,223
That's all right.

868
01:20:46,564 --> 01:20:52,547
This money could be used, Mr. President, not only for repaving a street, it's also used for sidewalks,

869
01:20:53,095 --> 01:21:00,977
handicap accessibility, maintenance on the water and sewer, so if it's a manhole cover or a catch basin, that Chapter 90 money can be used for that.

870
01:21:01,837 --> 01:21:12,100
And I think we're falling short of the mark in a city this size, six, seven square miles with 91 miles of road and fixing our roads.

871
01:21:12,580 --> 01:21:21,683
And it may seem like a minor thing, but it's a major thing for traffic in this community, for pedestrian safety, and for our residents.

872
01:21:22,019 --> 01:21:26,240
that have to traverse these streets that are littered and lined with potholes.

873
01:21:26,580 --> 01:21:31,482
We know we have streets in the community that we've discussed six decades.

874
01:21:33,102 --> 01:21:35,163
Six decades never repaved.

875
01:21:36,443 --> 01:21:41,225
What do you think a street looks like after six decades of a New England weather?

876
01:21:41,785 --> 01:21:45,106
New England snow, plowing, salt, everything else.

877
01:21:46,026 --> 01:21:47,247
What do you think the street looks like?

878
01:21:48,027 --> 01:21:50,928
And we all know what it looks like because we all went down to some of these streets.

879
01:21:52,316 --> 01:21:56,440
So Mr. President, you know what, I will support the budget this year.

880
01:21:56,480 --> 01:22:04,747
Last year, I voted against the budget for a number of reasons that I was unhappy with, of which some of those reasons found their way in the budget this year.

881
01:22:05,488 --> 01:22:10,233
And there is one other issue that I would like to mention.

882
01:22:11,133 --> 01:22:14,857
It was this council back, I believe it was two or three years ago,

883
01:22:15,458 --> 01:22:24,420
that offered a resolution, it was actually my resolution, requesting that a line item be placed in the budget for arts in the community.

884
01:22:24,940 --> 01:22:31,802
It was the first time, it was supported unanimously by this council, it was the first time ever we had a line item for arts in the community.

885
01:22:32,442 --> 01:22:35,983
And I'm very proud of that, and at the time Mayor McGlynn, I think, funded it.

886
01:22:36,947 --> 01:22:46,791
maybe 15,000, and we made a promise to the art community at the time, because the state, you know, when they start making their cuts, which they're doing now, the arts is the first to get cut.

887
01:22:47,592 --> 01:22:50,873
And I've always stated, that's our biggest bang for our buck.

888
01:22:51,373 --> 01:22:58,997
When you see 15 to $30,000, it goes to thousands of children and programs within this community that keep this city functioning.

889
01:22:59,737 --> 01:23:06,220
And the following year, I think it was Mayor McGlynn or Mayor Burke, it might have been Mayor McGlynn,

890
01:23:06,650 --> 01:23:09,572
we requested as the council that we double it to $30,000.

891
01:23:09,752 --> 01:23:23,680
And not just giving money away, the Arts Council came to us and said, this is what the programming went for, this is how the outreach went, this is how many people we touched in the community, these are the projects, and I thought it was a home run, Mr. President.

892
01:23:24,080 --> 01:23:33,065
This year I asked her the budget deliberation, if we can look at adding to the $30,000, and I didn't get any support from the administration again.

893
01:23:33,405 --> 01:23:36,487
However, as far as I know, the arts funding,

894
01:23:37,194 --> 01:23:44,900
and I stand to be corrected on this, has been slashed by at least 45% their budget, Mr. President, from state and federal funding.

895
01:23:45,281 --> 01:23:46,301
It has been slashed by at least 45%.

896
01:23:47,663 --> 01:23:53,647
So they count on our measly $15,000 or $30,000 to run all these different events.

897
01:23:54,068 --> 01:24:03,455
Everyone likes to go out to circle the square and the river at the Hatch Shell and all these other events they run, and funding has to come somewhere.

898
01:24:04,276 --> 01:24:06,578
And I was happy we stepped up to the plate

899
01:24:06,938 --> 01:24:14,599
But I am disappointed this year, Mr. President, that we couldn't find additional money to support the arts movement in our community.

900
01:24:14,659 --> 01:24:23,261
So based on those few things, Mr. President, I'm hoping next year will be a different case from the streets and from the arts.

901
01:24:23,981 --> 01:24:27,102
And I will move approval on this budget, Mr. President.

902
01:24:27,202 --> 01:24:27,662
Thank you.

903
01:24:28,202 --> 01:24:30,082
On the motion by Councilor DelaRusso.

904
01:24:31,062 --> 01:24:31,342
Second.

905
01:24:33,803 --> 01:24:34,823
Name and address of the record, please.

906
01:24:37,566 --> 01:24:51,434
Mr. President, if other Councillors want to speak on the budget, by the way, Councillor DelaRusso's motion was on the school budget, not on the city budget.

907
01:24:52,975 --> 01:24:57,738
So that motion does not affect what's on the floor right now.

908
01:24:57,758 --> 01:25:05,082
But what I did want to say is that following the protocol, if there are other Councillors who want to speak on the budget,

909
01:25:05,437 --> 01:25:07,739
total city budget before I do.

910
01:25:08,459 --> 01:25:14,504
There are counselors do want to speak before you do, but they're giving me the floor now.

911
01:25:14,664 --> 01:25:15,565
I appreciate that.

912
01:25:15,585 --> 01:25:19,188
Well, I want to thank you, uh, Mr. President.

913
01:25:19,788 --> 01:25:25,973
And also I want to thank the whole city council whom I consider my friends and neighbors.

914
01:25:26,954 --> 01:25:33,079
I want my relationship to the council to be the same as the council's relationship to the people.

915
01:25:34,360 --> 01:25:37,121
and that is one of support and service.

916
01:25:38,242 --> 01:25:49,666
First, I want to express my appreciation to the city council for its many days of attendance at the review of the 2018 budget as presented by our mayor.

917
01:25:51,027 --> 01:25:59,551
The council listened to all the department heads and asked questions about details in the budget, and you are well informed.

918
01:26:00,551 --> 01:26:02,652
The council takes an oath to support

919
01:26:03,467 --> 01:26:06,048
and defend the Massachusetts constitution.

920
01:26:06,788 --> 01:26:13,529
And our constitution is there to serve the people and the city, which I know our counselors love.

921
01:26:14,729 --> 01:26:18,990
The city council is not elected to serve the mayor.

922
01:26:20,651 --> 01:26:27,692
There are about 37 items in the budget whose costs can be reduced by a simple majority vote of the council.

923
01:26:28,492 --> 01:26:32,793
However, the council is not allowed to increase the budget

924
01:26:34,260 --> 01:26:36,841
That is how we get checks and balances.

925
01:26:37,842 --> 01:26:44,766
The council is empowered to check the mayor if it thinks there are excesses in a budget.

926
01:26:49,268 --> 01:26:55,972
I know the council is aware of all this, but I say it in order to inform the television audience.

927
01:26:57,910 --> 01:27:02,292
The 2018 budget amounts to $167 million.

928
01:27:02,472 --> 01:27:08,374
That is $5 million more than last year's budget of $162 million.

929
01:27:09,134 --> 01:27:26,380
If the city council passes this budget, it is voting today right now to raise taxes on all the people of Medford, including senior citizens, fixed income residents, and minimum wage earners.

930
01:27:27,770 --> 01:27:34,013
I don't think the council wants to do that, but that is what will happen if this budget is passed.

931
01:27:34,954 --> 01:27:42,798
That tax increase amounts to four to $500 more for each taxpayer.

932
01:27:42,818 --> 01:27:45,840
$400 is very painful to our vulnerable people.

933
01:27:47,340 --> 01:27:55,985
The budget spending is $167 million and more than 80% of that goes to compensation for city of Medford employees

934
01:27:56,670 --> 01:28:02,773
And those loyal employees will continue to be rewarded, but we will not tolerate waste by others.

935
01:28:03,714 --> 01:28:04,815
Let me repeat that.

936
01:28:05,535 --> 01:28:11,838
Our loyal employees will continue to be rewarded, but we will not tolerate waste by others.

937
01:28:12,679 --> 01:28:16,621
That leaves less than 20% for materiel and supplies.

938
01:28:17,822 --> 01:28:25,606
And that explains why Medford cannot carry out proper and timely maintenance, as Councilor Marks said,

939
01:28:26,165 --> 01:28:29,746
of buildings, infrastructure, and natural resources.

940
01:28:31,366 --> 01:28:38,949
Heads of departments, out of respect for the executive, do not insist on proper allocation of funds for their departments.

941
01:28:39,749 --> 01:28:43,710
But department heads need and want proper allocation.

942
01:28:44,550 --> 01:28:48,071
As a result, potholes are not filled.

943
01:28:49,712 --> 01:28:51,172
Sidewalks are not repaired.

944
01:28:52,749 --> 01:28:54,810
Street bumps are not maintained.

945
01:28:55,890 --> 01:28:57,411
Speed bumps, rather, sorry.

946
01:28:57,971 --> 01:28:59,511
Speed bumps are not maintained.

947
01:29:00,472 --> 01:29:02,272
Crosswalks are not painted.

948
01:29:03,093 --> 01:29:04,813
And that was promised in a campaign.

949
01:29:06,194 --> 01:29:07,794
Street cleaning is sparse.

950
01:29:08,755 --> 01:29:10,135
Trees are not trimmed.

951
01:29:11,136 --> 01:29:13,336
Tree stumps are not removed for many months.

952
01:29:14,757 --> 01:29:17,238
Underground water leaks are not repaired.

953
01:29:18,458 --> 01:29:20,779
Roof leaks are not repaired.

954
01:29:22,490 --> 01:29:24,751
Public toilets are not sanitary.

955
01:29:25,892 --> 01:29:28,613
Medford Square is not made to work.

956
01:29:29,733 --> 01:29:33,735
Traffic lights at dangerous intersections have not been synchronized.

957
01:29:34,956 --> 01:29:38,777
No foot patrol police officers, as promised in the campaign.

958
01:29:40,118 --> 01:29:43,339
No end of unpopular kiosk parking program.

959
01:29:44,660 --> 01:29:45,740
No charter review.

960
01:29:47,121 --> 01:29:51,403
No improvement in public school abysmal MCAS ranking.

961
01:29:53,127 --> 01:29:58,691
and $25 for a permit to park in front of your own house.

962
01:30:01,013 --> 01:30:03,575
Is this what we are paying high taxes for?

963
01:30:05,136 --> 01:30:05,837
Let's face it.

964
01:30:07,198 --> 01:30:09,840
Our Medford is not a vital city.

965
01:30:10,821 --> 01:30:12,742
The city's finances are unstable.

966
01:30:13,843 --> 01:30:18,927
Its head is bumping the ceiling when 80% of the budget is spent on the bureaucracy.

967
01:30:20,048 --> 01:30:20,348
Soon,

968
01:30:21,623 --> 01:30:26,345
For all practical purposes, the city will become a welfare department.

969
01:30:27,585 --> 01:30:45,531
If the council passes this budget, it becomes responsible for raising taxes and it must be held responsible by the voters for separating the people from their money without an improvement in services and then redistributing that money to prosperous people.

970
01:30:46,271 --> 01:30:49,372
Many of them, not even residents of Medford.

971
01:30:50,828 --> 01:30:58,431
To quote Oscar Wilde, our mayor knows the cost of everything and the value of nothing.

972
01:30:59,511 --> 01:31:14,756
To vote for this budget is to follow the mayor down that path of depression, and worse, to injure our very own children who will inherit a sad, poorly educated city.

973
01:31:16,056 --> 01:31:17,117
One last quotation.

974
01:31:18,177 --> 01:31:20,438
This is from Marcus Aurelius, who said,

975
01:31:21,688 --> 01:31:26,651
In a sense, people are our proper occupation.

976
01:31:27,931 --> 01:31:31,013
Our job is to do them good.

977
01:31:32,533 --> 01:31:33,134
Thank you, Mr. President.

978
01:31:33,154 --> 01:31:33,994
Thank you, Mr. President.

979
01:31:34,054 --> 01:31:34,614
Thank you, Governor.

980
01:31:35,475 --> 01:31:36,275
Councilor Falco.

981
01:31:37,196 --> 01:31:39,717
I will yield to the resident.

982
01:31:41,778 --> 01:31:42,218
Thank you.

983
01:31:42,238 --> 01:31:43,339
Name and address for the record, please.

984
01:31:43,759 --> 01:31:44,720
Thank you, Mr. President.

985
01:31:44,780 --> 01:31:47,221
Rob Capucci, 71 Evans Street.

986
01:31:47,261 --> 01:31:49,682
Through the chair, thank you, Councilor Falco, for yielding.

